@page
@model Htmxmas.Pages.Samples.Day_12.IndexModel

@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Day 12: Keyboard Shortcuts";
}

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-6">
        <markdown>
            # Day 12: Keyboard Shortcuts
            
            While clicking is a great way to interact with a web page, power users crave the ability to
            interact with a web page using the keyboard.
            
            This sample demonstrates how to use keyboard shortcuts to interact with a web page. Press any of the matching
            keyboard keys to trigger the appropriate button and interaction.
            
            ## How Does This Work?
            
            Htmx allows for the `hx-trigger` attribute to specify a keyboard shortcut. The `keyup` event is used
            to listen for the keyboard shortcut. The `key` attribute is used to specify the key that should be pressed.
            
            ```html
            <button class="btn btn-danger" hx-trigger="click, keyup[key=='h'||key=='H'] from:body"
                    hx-post hx-page="Index" hx-page-handler="Card" hx-route-card="hat">
                H
            </button>
            ```
            
            It's important to note that the `from:body` is needed, since the event is triggered from the body of the page. We also
            listen for casing variants of the specific letter key. You can also listen for multiple keys to be pressed at once for a
            more complex shortcut.
        </markdown>
        
        @await Html.PartialAsync("_Paging", new PagingModel(12))
    </div>
    <div class="col-6">
        <style>
            #card.htmx-added {
                opacity: 0;
            }

            #card {
                opacity: 1;
                transition: opacity 1s ease-out;
            }
        </style>

        <div class="card text-center">
            <div class="card-header">
                <h2>Keyboard Shortcuts</h2>
                
            </div>
            <div class="card-body">
